segments.text: So you talked a little bit about Black Power, but what impact do you think that they had then, like Stokely Carmichael and the Panthers?
I think they had a, you needed all of those things at the time.
You needed all of those things.
I'm not, even though it was a, I was philosophically opposed to the so-called Black Power.
You know, one of the things that, you know, your parents teach you, they teach
Your parents really teach you right.
They teach you right.
And what my parents told me, always said, look, you're no better than nobody else.
And you're no worse than nobody else.
You're the same.
You're a man, just like anybody else.
You put on your pants like them, the same way you bleed red blood.
Your brain, your body.
Physiologically, it's the same.
You just got a different skin hue in your hair.
Maybe a little different.
But basically, you can take one part and put it in another person.
And I think philosophically, the black power thing alluded to somehow you wanted to dominate and be the person on top.
But that's not what you really wanted.
You just wanted equal opportunity.
Right.
Not to dominate anybody else, because if you did, you were no better than the person that you, you know, you could just replace one with another.
Mm-hmm.
And, uh, but it did scare people of what would happen, because there were a lot of places in the South where blacks were the majority.
Mm-hmm.
A lot of counties, my county, Pike County, Alabama, blacks were in the majority.
My hometown, blacks were in the majority of the population.
And this kind of a thing scared those people.
And it helped galvanize support.
Sometimes that, you know, you wouldn't have gotten.
And it also turned people against you.
That was a place for everybody.
I mean, looking back at it, that was a place for everybody.

But at the time, trying to adhere to what Dr. King's philosophy was and what have you, this was totally out of kilter with what those, I guess you might call them, disciples, people who would listen to him, and this nonviolent movement and what have you.
a totally different way.
Totally opposite, right?
Yeah, totally opposite of what he was trying to say or do.
So, uh, to me and a lot of the people, uh, it was then, look, if I graduate from college, I want, you know, the same opportunity at a job.
I want the same pay.
I just stopped by.
All right.
I'll holler at you.
Okay.
All right.
Uh, uh,
I want the same opportunity.
I don't want any more.
You know, sort of like today they talk about quotas and things.
Well, whites interpret this as saying blacks, because you're black, you want a white man's job.
That should be an equal number.
But nobody, and I guess I'm one of the old timers, I guess, now.
I don't want, I'm opposed to quotas.
But how else can you get an equal number of blacks into a position?
Because people are people.
I have a business here.
Who am I going to hire?
Blacks.
You're going to hire people that you know, your friends and what have you.
And because our society is, and until
Like, I hope my daughters don't have to do this.
I have to send my daughters to Allen Academy and Montessori School.
And like this weekend, a lot of her friends or personal friends or wife went out to a slumber party and this kind of a thing.
These kids will have this personal relationship.
I never had that type of, except, you know, the fella down the street from me.
And it was a tenuous type thing at best.
that we had, you know, sometimes.
Was that your friend in Alabama?
Yeah.
Yeah, it was a tenuous type thing at best, you know.
Although we felt close to each other, he felt the pressure from the white community.
I felt the pressure from the black community.
And, you know, at the time we didn't really understand it, but
We knew it was something else there, you know, what was going on.
So, you know, that black power thing, the philosophy of the black power thing was not what the old, how do you say it?
I don't want to say the old, and I sound like I'm ancient and antique.
But the people who were like in the original, in the early beginnings of it,
who were taught the nonviolent techniques and procedures and things like this, it just didn't sit real well with you.
So you think it was more the younger men, even more the ones that were younger?
No, I think people like Carmichael and what have you, they thought that by demanding these kind of things and threatening people and what have you, that they could get more.
And they did help.
But in the end, if you carried it out to the end, it was self-defeating.
If you carried what they were saying out to the end, it was self-defeating.
What the nonviolent movement strove to do was to make people so ashamed of themselves that they would do what was right.
In other words, you changed that person's heart, not did it
Because he had to, or was forced to.
You know, people who were claiming them.
Make the other people, make the white, or the people that have been repressing, feel like, realize what they've been doing.
What they've been doing, yeah.
It was wrong.
And then when it comes from that person, you have a better chance than somebody that's standing up and wasn't going to make it.
Right.
Sort of like church, you know, parents make you go to church.
But until you have been converted, it doesn't really mean much.
So just I guess this is one more thing I just wanted to ask you about the Black Panthers.
I never knew much about the Black Panthers.
Really?
No.
That was like on the West.
They weren't very popular in the South.
No, they weren't.
people admired them.
And you know, they were ultra-vile.
But I never, I met a few of them, but they were just, how do you say, they were just too far for me.
And I say I, when I say me,

I'm talking about, and maybe I shouldn't, I should only speak for myself, but speaking with a lot of my old friends, like Bill Frazier, John Lewis, and people like this, when we talk, we don't want to do that.
You can't win in the end.
You just can't.
The white man controls the military, and how are you going to win a war?
You can't do it.
So we just talked a little bit about some of the programs they did in a lot of the ghettos and some of their social programs as well as we talked a lot about there.
Did y'all hear more about the violence or did y'all hear more about the?
We heard about the social program.
But here and again, how were these things financed?
Some people got scared.
and gave them some money because they didn't want these niggas to blow this place away.
Is that how they got a lot of it?
A lot of it.
I mean, that's oversimplifying.
Right.
But what you wanted, you wanted nobody to take care of you.
You wanted the ability to do for yourself.
And a lot of that, by doing that, that

in and of itself still made you a slave that's again that's always because you were still depending on what somebody else it did not give you the the ability to you know do it for yourself or be yourself and even though you had this big gun you were still no better than the sharecropper who was depending on this
man for his land and wanted to buy seed and all this kind of thing.
And this is not that I'm out of it and that it's removed from it.

These are some of the things that a lot of the young kids, youngsters like myself, a lot of the things we discussed when options and people came around trying to get you to start these chapters and look at this, what we really want to do.
And what would have come in the end?
A lot more violence, I guess, obviously.
Yeah, and what you can't win.

Well, I just wanted to ask you, and I guess some wrap-up questions are, I just wanted to ask you about, well, what impacted the deaths of both Malcolm, I mean, since they were both different, totally opposite extremes, almost, in a lot of ways, Malcolm and Martin had on the...
especially Martin, had on the civil rights movement, you think, when his death came?
Malcolm's legacy, I think, came after his death.
He had a few followers.
Statistically, there are very few American blacks who follow Islam.
the Muslim movement, which he espoused.
And even Malcolm himself divorced himself from that particular philosophy, the separatists and all this kind of a crowd.
So I think that the words Malcolm, like the book Malcolm X, if you ever read that book, I think what he said, even himself was converted in the end.
To his ideal or to Christian or to his ideal?
What do you mean his ideal?
His overall philosophy.
See, the black Muslim preaches this thing about separation, and superiority, and all of this kind of stuff.
Malcolm, you know, in writing this book, it didn't quite come out like that.
It was a little bit different.
what the so-called black Muslim movement was about.
And most people in the black community feel for that reason, why the Muslim killer.
Because he was one of their better known spokespersons and what have you.
And for him to break with what they were saying, how do you say it?
cast a black eye on what they were espousing.
Martin Luther King, on the other hand, I think, not taking anything away from Martin Luther King, but I think the time, I think sometimes events make a man, rather than a man making events.
Even though King was well prepared for it and everything like that, I think events and people had a lot to do with making King.
Of course, he had the right things to say to take advantage of these things and what have you.
The loss of King was a loss because he affected more people.
His way of trying to bring about
change affected more people.
You take like the women's rights movement came out of the civil rights movement, lesbians and gays, Hispanics.
All of these things were like as a result of Martin Luther King and the civil rights movement.
So I think
King's death temporarily put a halt to it.
Even though some people may disagree with me, I think that because King was so far ahead of his time, he lost a lot of his popularity because of issues that he took, like the Vietnam War.
But ultimately, he was right.
But at the time, when he was saying it, people would say, hey, this man is unpatriotic.
He's a communist and all this kind of thing.
But he was right.
A lot of things that he said that tarnished him while he was living somewhat later proved to be true.
So I think he was a thinker who was having been put in that role.
He made the best of it.
I guess in a way, it's kind of like Churchill in England.
Having been put in that role, he had the wherewithal to handle it.
So it was definitely a loss to the black community, particularly symbolically of what the black community really want.
You had a lot of people after him who went off in different directions.
which only helped to divide the movement, I think.
You didn't have a solidarity or one voice or one philosophy that had been proven to win.
And your leader, I guess, it just seemed like.
Well, I think a lot of people look at that a lot differently than I do.
He was symbolic of leadership, but there were other men in the South who were, they didn't have a national following or scope or they were not as eloquent as King.
But I think a lot of people tend to think in the black community they got this one chief and a whole bunch of Indians.
But it's just like the white community.
You got a lot of people who think independently.
They're not going to follow anybody.
They're going to do what they want to do, you know.
But I think for the time and for the 60s and whatever, King was the right man.
And I think that his legacy will live on because not only was he good for blacks, he was good for whites.
He was good for the country.
He was a black man, but what he espoused was good for the country.
even though we are still struggling with this thing.
Just think, if we didn't spend a lot of our money and time and resources on this type of thing, how much better of a country we would be if we could adequately challenge the Japanese.
There's no limit to what we can do, but we spend a lot of our energy still
superior and inferior type things.
You know, you look at the university out there, you hear all kinds of things about this group going, this rights, and all of this kind of a thing.
Wasting time and money.
Dr. Mullen would be better spending his time, you know, maybe doing something in the veterinary medicine department or whatever.
Instead of spending his time with Ray's relations, that shouldn't even be...
So you think he should just...
I don't think I exactly understand that.

Well, what I'm saying is, when you take a lot of your time and energy, take for instance you and I, or let's say if I own a business, and say, if I had to spend a lot of my resources and time figuring out a way
I find I'm going to keep some white person out.
That's time lost that I could have been using in a positive manner to make more money, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.
And I'm saying that we still waste a lot of time and money with the problem that, and yet we have more churches than any place in the world.
Christian churches anyway.
And we don't live up to what we say we are.
Well, yeah, I understand what you're talking about.
I mean, I understand where you're coming from.
You know, you go to any church on a Sunday morning, it's still the most segregated hour in the nation.
It is, isn't it?
And this is where everybody's supposed to be equal and right and all that.
I tell people this.
I don't only say this to whites.
I tell people in our church, hey, why don't we go out and try to get some white converts or Hispanic converts?
Even at the daycare, I found it.
And I told them that if we developed a daycare that was a very good daycare, whites would come, and they have.
In the Bryant community?
Yeah, out of the church.
They could come to the daycare.
We had whites there.
Hispanics there.
But we spent so much time trying to...
Prior to that time, we were trying to keep that little thing.
It was a good daycare.
We were trying to keep it...
to ourselves, you know.
But here you are, every Sunday morning, you get up talking about God, and you've been changed, and all of this kind of a thing, which, you know, attracts to it.

And that, and that's the whole, that's the whole underpinning of the, it seemed like, to me, I mean, that's a lot of the Christianity, or the beliefs and the values of that were a lot of the whole, under the whole civil rights movement.
Right.
I mean, the non-violence and
Take a page from Jesus.
That's all.
Okay.
That's really all the questions I had for you and stuff.
I really enjoyed talking with you.
It was an experience.
It was a time.
I'm very fortunate.
I feel very fortunate and happy that I lived in those times.
A pivotal point.
so-called in American history.
And I feel that I'm a better person as a result of it.
However, as an American, I can see that we still have a long ways to go, a lot of things to do.
And I'm not going to ever waste my energy hating anybody.
I waste my energy in a detrimental fashion.
I still want equality and everything like that.
But hate and this kind of thing.
I heard a man say one time that if you're going to keep a pig in the mud, you have to get in that mud.
So if one person wanted to hold somebody else down, he got to get down to that person.
You can't stay up there.
The slave owner, it brought him down a notch or two.
He had to do what he had to do to control his slaves.
You couldn't take the high road.
And as I said, the lessons that I learned from that period of time
I don't think any schooling or anything could have taught me what I learned as a result of it.
I'm sure your children, do you just have one daughter?
Oh, I have five children.
Do you?
Yeah.
But I'm sure that they know a lot about, do you think that a lot, for the most of the black community realizes, I mean a lot of the younger generation now,
They don't know what happened.
They don't know what is happening.
I think TV and the instant syndrome has really gotten the best of America, black and white.
Because I watch TV, I let my kids watch it, but you have to put it in its proper place.
We've replaced instant things with the ability to read and write and do mathematics.
We've replaced the thought process with the computer, almost.
You don't really have to think you're programmed to write things.
My kids, I try to teach them.
I teach them that they are black.
But they just happen to be black, just the way the cards were built.
There's no stigmatism to being that way.
And just like there's no stigmatism to that person being white.
And I teach them to respect everybody, regardless
We have all kinds of people at my house all the time.
We had, when the Russian delegation came.
Oh, did y'all have one of the students over there?
No, we had the whole group at our house, yeah.
Really?
I didn't know that.
When they came here to the university and stuff?
Came to the university, came to our house.
We fed them, you know, food.
I want my kids to know everybody.
And when it all boils down, you know, like my mom and dad told me, you know,
They bleed red blood, you know.
It's insane.
It's just what you yourself choose to be.
I sure did.
One of my daughters is still in Montessori school.
Well, both of them are in Montessori school.
But they're friends.
You know, they have Orleans, they have Indians, they have everything there.
And I want them to know that even though that school is, how do you say it, sort of like an island, it really is the way that society should be for everybody that accepts.
I mean, I want them to know what the reality is, but I also want them to have a feeling of what it should be.
I want them to know about the blacks who made contributions, but I don't want them to become immersed in blackness.
Because if you get immersed in blackness, you forget about all the other people.
Your tunnel vision.
Yeah.
I don't want them to do that.
I want them to know.
Like I said, I know it's impossible under today's circumstances to give them the type of education that I got.
What do you mean, your experience education?
Yeah, the experience, yeah.
But, you know, like, I want them to know people.
My daughter knows Ann Richards.
Ann Richards gave her a letter.
Took pictures with Ann Richards.
She also took pictures with Benjamin Hook.
Oh, really?
I went and heard him speak last, when he came in.
Was that when she went and saw him?
Yeah.
We had a reception for him out of Diagon Alley in Ramada.
Oh.
And, you know, I want her to know everybody, that a man is a man is a man is a man.
You know, just accept him as that.
And then you don't get all bogged up on these side issues.
You can go straight ahead.
Well, thank you for your time, sir.
I really appreciate it.
